  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The property next door sells, or the one across the street, or one a few houses up. Within days the result becomes the dominant reference point for everyone: neighbours, buyers, agents, and the seller themselves. The figure attaches to expectations on both sides of every conversation. The seller wonders whether their property is worth more, the buyers assume it is the new ceiling, and the agent has to talk through what the sale actually tells the market. A neighbour's sale is one of the most powerful comparables you will encounter in any campaign, and one of the most commonly misread.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why neighbour sales are powerful comparables</h2>
      <p>Directly equivalent location, same suburb dynamics, same school catchment, same access to the same train station, the same shops, the same parks. The most recent data point in the local market, with all the local context already controlled for. Buyers and agents both reach for them first, because the relevance is so obvious that no other comparable seems to need explanation. That same obviousness is what makes neighbour sales easy to misinterpret.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The trap: direct equivalence is rare</h2>
      <p>The neighbour's house is not your house. Different size, different condition, different layout, different presentation, different marketing campaign, different motivation of the seller. Treating the neighbour's sale as 'what your house is worth' is usually wrong, because the differences between two properties on the same street can easily be worth $100,000 or more once you account for renovation, aspect, level, and the specifics of the campaign that produced the result. The closer the comparable, the more important the differences become.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What makes a strong comparable</h2>
      <p>Similar size and bedroom count, similar land area, similar age and condition, similar aspect and street position, similar level of recent renovation. The closer those line up, the more directly the result reads across to your property. When all of them line up, the neighbour's sale is the strongest single comparable a campaign will get. When most of them line up but one or two diverge meaningfully, the comparable still informs the analysis, but it requires explicit adjustment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What makes a weak comparable</h2>
      <p>Different bedroom or bathroom count, renovated versus unrenovated, different property type (house versus townhouse), off-market or private sale (which produces a result without buyer competition), deceased estate or distressed sale (where the compressed timeline often produces a lower price than a normal campaign would). Any of these can pull the result several percent below or above what a comparable open-market campaign on a similar property would achieve.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to interpret the neighbour's result</h2>
      <p>Three questions discipline the interpretation. Is the result consistent with broader market evidence (3 to 5 comparable sales)? If yes, it is a credible reference. Is it a single-data outlier? If yes, treat with caution; one number does not redefine the suburb's price level. Did the property have specific issues or features that explain the result? If yes, adjust accordingly, and document the adjustment so the conversation with buyers stays grounded in the differences rather than getting stuck on the headline number.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers do with the neighbour's sale</h2>
      <p>Buyers anchor strongly to the most recent local sale, often more strongly than the comparable warrants. They apply that anchor to your property even when adjustments are needed, and they may push for a similar price even if your property is genuinely different. The behavioural pattern is well documented: the most recent number wins disproportionate weight in negotiation, regardless of how comparable it actually is. The seller's job is not to argue the buyer out of using the comparable, but to make sure the right adjustments are visible in the conversation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do as a seller</h2>
      <p>Build a case using 3 to 5 comparables, not just the neighbour. Explicitly identify the differences between your property and the neighbour's, and quantify them where you can. Include the comparison in the agent's pricing discussion with buyers, so the neighbour's sale is presented in context rather than as a standalone reference. The goal is not to discredit the neighbour's result, it is to position your property correctly within the broader evidence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What NOT to do</h2>
      <p>Do not let one neighbour sale set your asking price up or down without analysis. Do not ignore the neighbour's sale either; buyers will reference it whether you do or not, and ignoring it cedes the framing to them. Do not get into a public dispute with the neighbour about price; that conversation never produces a useful outcome and often reaches buyers indirectly through the suburb's social network. The agent should handle the comparison professionally, not the seller emotionally.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The agent's responsibility</h2>
      <p>A good agent acknowledges the neighbour's sale openly, presents the broader comparable evidence, and walks buyers through the differences that justify a higher or lower position. An agent who pretends the neighbour's sale does not exist looks evasive. An agent who lets the neighbour's number anchor the entire conversation has not done the work to position the property correctly. The right behaviour sits in the middle: acknowledge, contextualise, and adjust.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The timing factor</h2>
      <p>A 6-month-old neighbour sale is less relevant than a 2-month-old one. In a moving market, even recent sales can become outdated quickly, particularly through interest rate changes or supply shifts. The further the comparable sits behind the current market, the more it needs broader context to remain useful. A sale from last year is interesting; a sale from last month is binding evidence that the neighbour's result reflects today's market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The inverse case: your sale becomes the comparable</h2>
      <p>Your sale will become the comparable for the next neighbour to sell. The price you achieve will affect their campaign, and through them, the broader street's expectations. This should not change your strategy, you sell on the merits of your campaign, not for the benefit of the next seller, but it is worth noting. Brisbane's inner east is a network of streets where the comparables are tight and the next seller is rarely far behind.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Use the neighbour's sale as one data point among several. Explicitly identify the differences between your property and theirs, and document them. Communicate the comparison thoughtfully to buyers and your agent, and avoid letting a single nearby result anchor expectations in either direction. The campaign that handles a neighbour's sale well is the one that brings the broader evidence to every conversation, so the headline number sits in context rather than dominating it.</p>

